comments: I call BS. I wish this wasn't so unrealistic. Great white sharks only breach near seal island and in false bay which are both located in South Africa. There has never been a reported sighting of a shark breaching in Australia. Also, if a shark did attack one of the guys swimming, then they almost certainly would not have attacked the second guy, let alone chase him down to the rock. Great white sharks have very, very sensitive teeth, as soon as they bite into you and realize that you do not have the fat density that they need for their diet (like a seal), they usually lose interest except for in cases of extreme hunger. A shark would never, never wait around a rock waiting for a person to jump in the water. The shark would have swam away within minutes of the first attack.

comments: I don't think the directors intended for this film to be just another dry pbs period piece, based exactly on the book with music true to the time. What people don't seem to get is that these characters lived in a racy era... where the rich were having affairs, were insanely drunk during prohibition, and were doing just as many scandalous/illicit activities if not even more than what celebrities do now. The music fits in my opinion, because it presents the seductively extravagant lifestyle the upper class of the roaring twenties had, in a way that the conservative jazz of the time could not. In this case, older music distances the protagonists of the story from the viewer, but using new music reminds us that Gatsby, Daisy, Tom, Myrtle, and Jordan are full of the same vibrant energy seen in the young and rich today.

In Japanese-occupied Korea, a conman operating under the sobriquet of "Count Fujiwara" hires a pickpocket named Sook-hee from a family of con artists to become the maid of the mysterious Japanese heiress Lady Hideko, whom Fujiwara plans to marry and to commit to an asylum in order to steal her inheritance. Sook-hee, taking on the name "Tamako", enters Hideko's household, which is controlled by her authoritarian Uncle Kouzuki. Hideko is haunted by the suicide of her aunt, and claims to hear her voice at night. As Sook-hee and Hideko spend more time together, they appear to get along well, Hideko allowing Sook-hee to wear her dresses and jewelry. Hideko is also anxious about marrying Fujiwara, her feelings for him not very strong, but Sook-hee makes passionate love to her, promising her the same pleasures with her new husband. Sook-hee begins expressing reluctance about following through with the plan, unhappy over the feigned attraction Fujiwara has for Hideko. Hideko herself feels that she cannot go through with the marriage, but Sook-hee insists she do so, causing Hideko to slap her and run away in frustration. Kouzuki leaves on business for a week, reminding Hideko to "always remember the basement." Hideko and Fujiwara elope soon afterward and consummate their marriage, as indicated by a small blood stain on Hideko's sheets the following morning. After cashing out Hideko's inheritance, Sook-hee, Hideko, and Fujiwara travel to the asylum, but Sook-Hee is taken away by the staff, having been told that she is in fact Hideko. After being left with one piece of jewelry by Hideko, Sook-hee curses them as she is carried away.

What a shame this movie only blames the banks while the Federal Reserve and big government regulations caused the housing bubble.

The Housing Bubble in 4 Easy Steps
SEPTEMBER 27, 2008 Mark Thornton

1. The Federal Reserve cut interest rates to as low as 1% so that after inflation we had negative interest rates.

2. As a result, mortgage rates fell to an all time low.

3. Low rates caused borrowing and lending to explode, particularly in real estate. For example, commercial banks more than doubled the amount of real-estate loans they made.

4. All these low interest loans had to be extended to people with worse credit ratings and this increased the demand for homes and other real-estate assets. It should not be surprising that home prices skyrocketed. Click on the link below to the Real Estate Roller Coaster:

Fannie Mae, Freddie Mac, mortgage-backed securities, and credit derivatives were simply the conduit that made all these bad loans and investments seem less risky than they really were. In this manner the Federal Reserve can fool the market, at least temporarily. In the end the market always reasserts itself.

comments: Nice
Awesome Superbad Official Trailer.

Storytime: When I was 15 this movie came to theaters, and my younger brother and I had to see it. Asked our parents to see it, and they bought the tickets and dropped us off. We walked to the ticket taker and he took the tickets, and we thought we were in the clear. As we were walking, he asked to see my ID. I told him "I forgot it" and he said...."Okay, well just don't come out of the theater." I said alright, and off to find a seat. My younger brother needed to take a piss about 30 minutes into the movie, and I told him "go ahead and go, screw it." He was about to walk into the hallway, but when he opened the door, someone saw him and watched him come sit back down. The rest of the movie, a different employee would come in and stare at us for a good 60 seconds, and leave. Literally the worst movie going experience of my life.

Great movie though. I watched it comfortably when it came out on "DVD" and it was amazing. That menu though.

comments: Just watched this movie. Great story and intense
The movie that made MW2

Awful. It's ridiculously slow, to where it drags the whole way. Even the action sequences aren't exciting. We ended up speeding it up to 1.5x and it was still tedious. Endless long, slow panning shots across deserts and suburbs and cities. The filmmakers tried to be profound, but it just comes across as sappy, which is very out of tune, considering the subject matter. It easily could've been 45 minutes shorter in the hands of a more talented director. Brolin's character is just a smiley psychopath, stuck in one superficial emotional gear without any nuance. Blunt was hardly any better, flat and boyish. She comes across as noble at first, but it's quickly obvious she's an emotionally dead woman living a seedy life, without self-respect or even much of a will to live. I wasn't sure why they bothered to cast a woman in this role at all, except maybe to meet some Hollywood quota. It felt off. Worse, she only seemed to be there to get beaten up and attacked over and over. :/

I can't believe this got such high reviews. It's literally dead on arrival. No high or low points, just flat-line all the way through. Do yourself a favor and pass on this one.

From Wikipedia:¬† "The paintings left Austria in March 2006 and were on display at the Los Angeles County Museum of Art until June 30, 2006. Months after the Austrian government returned Altmann's family's belongings, she consigned the Klimt paintings to auction house Christie's, to be sold on behalf of her family. The painting Portrait of Adele Bloch-Bauer I (1907) was sold to cosmetics heir Ronald Lauder for $135 million, at the time the highest sum ever paid for a painting. Since July 13, 2006, the painting has been on public display in the Neue Galerie in New York City, which was established by Lauder in 2001. The four additional works by Klimt were also exhibited at the Neue Gallerie for several weeks in 2006.[9]
In November 2006, Adele Bloch-Bauer II (1912) was sold at auction at Christie's in New York fetching almost $88 million. In total, the four remaining paintings sold at auction for $192.7 million; coupled with the Lauder-bought painting the sum total was approximately $325 million. The proceeds were divided up among several heirs."
